You are working in a git repo that deploys by pushing to GitHub:
Primary repo (origin): https://github.com/MatthewKehoeErgo/Matts-Ergo-Cursor-Prototype-v01
Optional mirror remote (sbci): https://github.com/MatthewKehoeErgo/SBCI-Cursor-Prototype-v01
Default branch: main

================================================================================
FAST PATH — fewer clicks than GitHub Desktop (prefer this for routine updates)
================================================================================
Goal: commit in Cursor, publish with one terminal command (no extra Desktop clicks).

Flow (recommended):
  1) Edit files in Cursor.
  2) Commit using Cursor’s Source Control: stage → message → Commit (built-in; no Desktop needed).
  3) Open the integrated terminal and run: `npm run deploy`
     (runs `git push origin main` — publishes to the Matts-Ergo repo).

One-liner when you prefer the terminal for everything (stage + commit + push):
  git add -A && git commit -m "Short description of change" && npm run deploy

Optional mirror to the SBCI repo after a successful deploy (only when needed):
  git push sbci main

================================================================================
FULL RULE — When the user asks to "deploy", "publish", "push", or "sync"
================================================================================

1) Verify repo state first
- Run: git status -sb
- Confirm branch is main (unless they asked for a feature branch).

2) Never commit secrets or local-only files
- Do NOT add: .env, *.key, *.pem, credentials files, local config, or large build artifacts.
- Keep node_modules/ and dist/ out of commits (.gitignore).

3) Keep commits small and readable
- Stage: git add -A (or specific paths)
- Commit message: one short line, e.g. "Update dashboard layout"

4) Push
- Normal / fast path: npm run deploy (same as git push origin main)
- Small change explicitly on main: git push origin main
- Larger / risky change: branch feature/<short-name>, push, open PR to main

5) Post-push verification
- git status -sb (clean, tracking origin/main)
